<DocsLayout title="What is a Zero-Day?">

<h1>What is a Zero-Day?</h1>

<p class="lead">
A <strong>zero-day vulnerability</strong> is a software flaw that's unknown
to the vendor, or known but not yet patched. The name comes from the fact
that the vendor has had <strong>zero days</strong> to fix it before it can
be exploited — which means the very first attack against it can succeed
with nothing standing in the way.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>Where the Name Actually Comes From</h2>

<p>
The term predates modern cybersecurity by decades. In the software piracy
scene of the 1990s, a "zero-day" release meant a cracked copy of a program
released on the same day it officially shipped — day zero. The security
community borrowed the phrase for a different kind of race: the gap between
a flaw becoming known to <em>someone</em> and a fix becoming available to
<em>everyone</em>.
</p>

<h2>Zero-Day Terminology</h2>

<p>
The word "zero-day" gets applied a bit loosely, but it actually covers
three distinct things:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Zero-day vulnerability</strong> — the underlying bug itself, before anyone has built a working attack against it.</li>
  <li><strong>Zero-day exploit</strong> — the actual code or technique that triggers the vulnerability.</li>
  <li><strong>Zero-day attack</strong> — the exploit being used against a real target, in the wild.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Once a patch exists but hasn't been applied everywhere, the vulnerability
is usually called an <strong>n-day</strong> instead — it's known, but still
dangerous to anyone who hasn't updated.
</p>

<h2>How Does a Zero-Day Happen?</h2>

<ol>
  <li>A hidden bug exists in software — often for years before anyone notices.</li>
  <li>A security researcher or attacker discovers it, usually through code review, fuzzing, or reverse engineering.</li>
  <li>If attackers find it first, they can build a working exploit and use it quietly.</li>
  <li>The vendor eventually learns about it — through responsible disclosure or by catching an attack in progress — and races to release a patch.</li>
</ol>

<h2>The Zero-Day Market</h2>

<p>
Not every zero-day gets reported to the vendor. There's an entire economy
built around them:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>White market</strong> — official bug bounty programs run by companies like Google, Apple, and Microsoft, paying researchers directly for responsibly disclosed bugs.</li>
  <li><strong>Gray market</strong> — brokers who buy exploits and sell access to governments and law enforcement agencies, operating in a legal but ethically contested space.</li>
  <li><strong>Black market</strong> — criminal marketplaces where exploits are sold to the highest bidder with no disclosure at all, often fueling ransomware and espionage.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Prices vary wildly by target: a working zero-click exploit for a fully
patched iPhone has reportedly sold for over a million dollars, since it
can bypass a device's security with zero user interaction.
</p>

<h2>Why Are Zero-Day Vulnerabilities Dangerous?</h2>

<ul>
  <li>They can be exploited before any patch exists — there's nothing to install to stop them.</li>
  <li>Traditional signature-based antivirus often can't detect a brand-new exploit it has never seen.</li>
  <li>They frequently target governments, critical infrastructure, and high-value individuals rather than random victims.</li>
  <li>A single zero-day can be reused across thousands of attacks before it's ever discovered.</li>
</ul>

<h2>A Preview: Stuxnet (2010)</h2>

<div class="example">
  <span class="idx">CASE STUDY</span>
  <h3>The most famous zero-day of all</h3>
  <p>
    Stuxnet remains one of the most sophisticated cyberweapons ever
    discovered. It chained together <em>four</em> separate Windows
    zero-days to physically sabotage centrifuges in Iran's nuclear program
    — proving that software exploits could cause real-world physical
    damage. The full story is covered in
    <a href={`${base}docs/case-studies`}>Case Studies</a>.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

<div class="tips">

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>Unknown</strong>
    <p>The vulnerability isn't publicly known or patched yet — attackers and defenders are on unequal footing.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>High Risk</strong>
    <p>Attackers can exploit systems before defenders even know there's something to fix.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>Protection</strong>
    <p>Fast patching, layered defenses, and responsible disclosure are what actually close the window.</p>
  </div>

</div>

